This privilege, however, is neither hurtful to a third person, nor very burthensome to the giver Í¾ and therefore within the propriety of the words, a lax rather than a striet interpretation is to be admitted3 and still more, if it be not a boon given on asking, but voluntarily offered: and more still, if, besides private convenience, some public utility is involved in it. Therefore the striet interpretation is to be rejected, even when the words imply it, except some absurdity would otherwise sellom or very probable conjectures of intention point that way. And on the other hand, a laxer interpretation, even not included in the propriety of the words, will be applicable, to avoid a similar absurdity, or upon very urgent conjectures.
